# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: neuroscience-fundamentals
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/blood-brain-barrier] The **blood–brain barrier** (**BBB**) is a highly selective semipermeable border of endothelial cells that regulates the transfer of solutes and chemicals between the circulatory system and the central nervous system, thus protecting the brain from harmful or unwanted substances in the blood.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/blood-brain-barrier] The blood–brain barrier is formed by endothelial cells of the capillary wall, astrocyte end-feet ensheathing the capillary, and pericytes embedded in the capillary basement membrane.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/blood-brain-barrier] This system allows the passage of some small molecules by passive diffusion, as well as the selective and active transport of various nutrients, ions, organic anions, and molecules such as glucose and amino acids that are crucial to neural function.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/blood-brain-barrier] The blood–brain barrier restricts the passage of pathogens, the diffusion of solutes in the blood, and large or hydrophilic molecules into the cerebrospinal fluid, while allowing the diffusion of hydrophobic molecules (O2, CO2, hormones) and small non-polar molecules.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/blood-brain-barrier] Cells of the barrier actively transport metabolic products such as glucose across the barrier using specific transport proteins.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/blood-brain-barrier] The barrier also restricts the passage of peripheral immune factors, like signaling molecules, antibodies, and immune cells, into the central nervous system, thus insulating the brain from damage due to peripheral immune events.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/blood-brain-barrier] Specialized brain structures participating in sensory and secretory integration within brain neural circuits—the circumventricular organs and choroid plexus—have in contrast highly permeable capillaries.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/blood-brain-barrier] The BBB results from the selectivity of the tight junctions between the endothelial cells of brain capillaries, restricting the passage of solutes.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/blood-brain-barrier] At the interface between blood and the brain, endothelial cells are adjoined continuously by these tight junctions, which are composed of smaller subunits of transmembrane proteins, such as occludin, claudins (such as Claudin-5), junctional adhesion molecule (such as JAM-A).
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/blood-brain-barrier] Each of these tight junction proteins is stabilized to the endothelial cell membrane by another protein complex that includes scaffolding proteins such as tight junction protein 1 (ZO1) and associated proteins.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/blood-brain-barrier] The BBB is composed of endothelial cells restricting passage of substances from the blood more selectively than endothelial cells of capillaries elsewhere in the body.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/blood-brain-barrier] Astrocyte cell projections called astrocytic feet (also known as "glia limitans") surround the endothelial cells of the BBB, providing biochemical support to those cells.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/blood-brain-barrier] The BBB is distinct from the quite similar blood-cerebrospinal fluid barrier, which is a function of the choroidal cells of the choroid plexus, and from the blood-retinal barrier, which can be considered a part of the whole realm of such barriers.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/blood-brain-barrier] Not all vessels in the human brain exhibit BBB properties.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/blood-brain-barrier] Some examples of this include the circumventricular organs, the roof of the third and fourth ventricles, capillaries in the pineal gland on the roof of the diencephalon and the pineal gland.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/blood-brain-barrier] The BBB appears to be functional by the time of birth.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/blood-brain-barrier] P-glycoprotein, a transporter, exists already in the embryonal endothelium.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/blood-brain-barrier] Measurement of brain uptake of various blood-borne solutes showed that newborn endothelial cells were functionally similar to those in adults, indicating that a selective BBB is operative at birth.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/blood-brain-barrier] The blood–brain barrier acts effectively to protect brain tissue from circulating pathogens and other potentially toxic substances.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/blood-brain-barrier] Accordingly, blood-borne infections of the brain are rare.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/blood-brain-barrier] Infections of the brain that do occur are often difficult to treat.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/blood-brain-barrier] Antibodies are too large to cross the blood–brain barrier, and only certain antibiotics are able to pass.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/blood-brain-barrier] In some cases, a drug has to be administered directly into the cerebrospinal fluid where it can enter the brain by crossing the blood-cerebrospinal fluid barrier.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/blood-brain-barrier] Circumventricular organs (CVOs) are individual structures located adjacent to the fourth ventricle or third ventricle in the brain, and are characterized by dense capillary beds with permeable endothelial cells unlike those of the blood–brain barrier.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/blood-brain-barrier] Included among CVOs having highly permeable capillaries are the area postrema, subfornical organ, vascular organ of the lamina terminalis, median eminence, pineal gland, and three lobes of the pituitary gland.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/blood-brain-barrier] Consequently, the CVO permeable capillaries are the point of bidirectional blood–brain communication for neuroendocrine function.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/blood-brain-barrier] The border zones between brain tissue "behind" the blood–brain barrier and zones "open" to blood signals in certain CVOs contain specialized hybrid capillaries that are leakier than typical brain capillaries, but not as permeable as CVO capillaries.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/blood-brain-barrier] Such zones exist at the border of the area postrema—nucleus tractus solitarii (NTS), and median eminence—hypothalamic arcuate nucleus.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/blood-brain-barrier] These zones appear to function as rapid transit regions for brain structures involved in diverse neural circuits—like the NTS and arcuate nucleus—to receive blood signals which are then transmitted into neural output.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/blood-brain-barrier] The blood–brain barrier is formed by the brain capillary endothelium and excludes from the brain 100% of large-molecule neurotherapeutics and more than 98% of all small-molecule drugs.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/blood-brain-barrier] Overcoming the difficulty of delivering therapeutic agents to specific regions of the brain presents a major challenge to treatment of most brain disorders.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/blood-brain-barrier] In its neuroprotective role, the blood–brain barrier functions to hinder the delivery of many potentially important diagnostic and therapeutic agents to the brain.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/blood-brain-barrier] Therapeutic molecules and antibodies that might otherwise be effective in diagnosis and therapy do not cross the BBB in adequate amounts to be clinically effective.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/blood-brain-barrier] To overcome this problem some peptides able to naturally cross the BBB have been widely investigated as a drug delivery system.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/blood-brain-barrier] Mechanisms for drug targeting in the brain involve going either "through" or "behind" the BBB.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/blood-brain-barrier] Modalities for drug delivery to the brain in unit doses through the BBB entail its disruption by osmotic means, or biochemically by the use of vasoactive substances, such as bradykinin, or even by localized exposure to high-intensity focused ultrasound (HIFU).
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/blood-brain-barrier] Some studies have shown that vectors targeting BBB transporters, such as the transferrin receptor, have been found to remain entrapped in brain endothelial cells of capillaries, instead of being ferried across the BBB into the targeted area.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/blood-brain-barrier] The brain can be targeted non-invasively via the nasal passage.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/blood-brain-barrier] However, these methods are less efficient to deliver drugs as they are indirect methods.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/blood-brain-barrier] Nanotechnology is under preliminary research for its potential to facilitate the transfer of drugs across the BBB.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/blood-brain-barrier] Capillary endothelial cells and associated pericytes may be abnormal in tumors and the blood–brain barrier may not always be intact in brain tumors.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/blood-brain-barrier] Other factors, such as astrocytes, may contribute to the resistance of brain tumors to therapy using nanoparticles.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/blood-brain-barrier] Fat-soluble molecules less than 400 daltons in mass can freely diffuse past the BBB through lipid-mediated passive diffusion.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/blood-brain-barrier] The blood–brain barrier may become damaged in certain neurological diseases, as indicated by neuroimaging studies of Alzheimer's disease, amyotrophic lateral sclerosis, epilepsy, hemorrhagic stroke, ischemic stroke, and brain trauma, and in systemic diseases, such as liver failure.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/blood-brain-barrier] However, in many neurodegenerative diseases, the exact cause and pathology remains unknown.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/blood-brain-barrier] An 1898 study observed that low-concentration "bile salts" failed to affect behavior when injected into the blood of animals.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/blood-brain-barrier] Thus, in theory, the salts failed to enter the brain.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/blood-brain-barrier] Two years later, Max Lewandowsky may have been the first to coin the term "blood–brain barrier" in 1900, referring to the hypothesized semipermeable membrane.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/blood-brain-barrier] There is some debate over the creation of the term *blood–brain barrier* as it is often attributed to Lewandowsky, but it does not appear in his papers.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/blood-brain-barrier] The creator of the term may have been Lina Stern.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/blood-brain-barrier] Stern was a Russian scientist who published her work in Russian and French.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/blood-brain-barrier] Due to the language barrier between her publications and English-speaking scientists, this could have made her work a lesser-known origin of the term.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/blood-brain-barrier] All the while, bacteriologist Paul Ehrlich was studying staining, a procedure that is used in many microscopy studies to make fine biological structures visible using chemical dyes.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/blood-brain-barrier] As Ehrlich injected some of these dyes (notably the aniline dyes that were then widely used), the dye stained all of the organs of some kinds of animals except for their brains.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/blood-brain-barrier] At that time, Ehrlich attributed this lack of staining to the brain simply not picking up as much of the dye.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/blood-brain-barrier] However, in a later experiment in 1913, Edwin Goldmann (one of Ehrlich's students) injected the dye directly into the cerebrospinal fluid of animal brains.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/blood-brain-barrier] He found then the brains did become dyed, but the rest of the body did not, demonstrating the existence of a compartmentalization between the two.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/blood-brain-barrier] At that time, it was thought that the blood vessels themselves were responsible for the barrier, since no obvious membrane could be found.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] The **central nervous system** (**CNS**) is the part of the nervous system consisting primarily of the brain, and the spinal cord.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] The retina is also technically part of the CNS.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] The CNS is named so because the brain integrates the received information and coordinates and influences the activity of all parts of the bodies of bilaterally symmetric and triploblastic animals—that is, all multicellular animals except sponges and diploblasts.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] It is a structure composed of nervous tissue positioned along the rostral (nose end) to caudal (tail end) axis of the body and may have an enlarged section at the rostral end which is a brain.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] Only arthropods, cephalopods and vertebrates have a true brain, though precursor structures exist in onychophorans, gastropods and lancelets.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] The rest of this article exclusively discusses the vertebrate central nervous system, which is radically distinct from all other animals.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] In vertebrates, the brain and spinal cord are both enclosed in the meninges.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] The meninges provide a barrier to chemicals dissolved in the blood, protecting the brain from most neurotoxins commonly found in food.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] Within the meninges the brain and spinal cord are bathed in cerebral spinal fluid which replaces the body fluid found outside the cells of all bilateral animals.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] In vertebrates, the CNS is contained within the dorsal body cavity, while the brain is housed in the cranial cavity within the skull.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] The spinal cord is housed in the spinal canal within the vertebrae.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] Within the CNS, the interneuronal space is filled with a large amount of supporting non-nervous cells called neuroglia or glia from the Greek for "glue".
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] In vertebrates, the CNS also includes the retina, and the optic nerve (cranial nerve II), as well as the olfactory nerves and olfactory epithelium.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] As parts of the CNS, they connect directly to brain neurons without intermediate ganglia.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] The olfactory epithelium is the only central nervous tissue outside the meninges in direct contact with the environment, which opens up a pathway for therapeutic agents which cannot otherwise cross the meninges barrier.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] The CNS consists of two major structures: the brain and spinal cord.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] The brain is encased in the skull, and protected by the cranium.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] The spinal cord is continuous with the brain and lies caudally to the brain.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] The spinal cord reaches from the base of the skull, and continues through or starting below the foramen magnum, and terminates roughly level with the first or second lumbar vertebra, occupying the upper sections of the vertebral canal.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] Microscopically, there are differences between the neurons and tissue of the CNS and the peripheral nervous system (PNS).
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] The CNS is composed of white and gray matter.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] This can also be seen macroscopically on brain tissue.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] The white matter consists of axons and oligodendrocytes, while the gray matter consists of neurons and unmyelinated fibers.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] Both tissues include a number of glial cells (although the white matter contains more), which are often referred to as supporting cells of the CNS.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] Astrocytes may be involved with both clearance of metabolites as well as transport of fuel and various beneficial substances to neurons from the capillaries of the brain.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] Upon CNS injury astrocytes will proliferate, causing gliosis, a form of neuronal scar tissue, lacking in functional neurons.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] The brain (cerebrum as well as midbrain and hindbrain) consists of a cortex, composed of neuron-bodies constituting gray matter, while internally there is more white matter that form tracts and commissures.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] Apart from cortical gray matter there is also subcortical gray matter making up a large number of different nuclei.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] From and to the spinal cord are projections of the peripheral nervous system in the form of spinal nerves (sometimes segmental nerves).
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] The nerves connect the spinal cord to skin, joints, muscles etc. and allow for the transmission of efferent motor as well as afferent sensory signals and stimuli.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] This allows for voluntary and involuntary motions of muscles, as well as the perception of senses.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] All in all 31 spinal nerves project from the brain stem, some forming plexa as they branch out, such as the brachial plexa, sacral plexa etc.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] Each spinal nerve will carry both sensory and motor signals, but the nerves synapse at different regions of the spinal cord, either from the periphery to sensory relay neurons that relay the information to the CNS or from the CNS to motor neurons, which relay the information out.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] The spinal cord relays information up to the brain through spinal tracts through the final common pathway to the thalamus and ultimately to the cortex.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] Apart from the spinal cord, there are also peripheral nerves of the PNS that synapse through intermediaries or ganglia directly on the CNS.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] These 12 nerves exist in the head and neck region and are called cranial nerves.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] Cranial nerves bring information to the CNS to and from the face, as well as to certain muscles (such as the trapezius muscle, which is innervated by accessory nerves as well as certain cervical spinal nerves).
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] Two pairs of cranial nerves; the olfactory nerves and the optic nerves are often considered structures of the CNS.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] This is because they do not synapse first on peripheral ganglia, but directly on CNS neurons.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] The olfactory epithelium is significant in that it consists of CNS tissue expressed in direct contact to the environment, allowing for administration of certain pharmaceuticals and drugs.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] At the anterior end of the spinal cord lies the brain.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] The brain makes up the largest portion of the CNS.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] It is often the main structure referred to when speaking of the nervous system in general.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] The brain is the major functional unit of the CNS.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] While the spinal cord has certain processing ability such as that of spinal locomotion and can process reflexes, the brain is the major processing unit of the nervous system.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] The brainstem consists of the medulla, the pons and the midbrain.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] The medulla can be referred to as an extension of the spinal cord, which both have similar organization and functional properties.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] The tracts passing from the spinal cord to the brain pass through here.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] Regulatory functions of the medulla nuclei include control of blood pressure and breathing.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] Other nuclei are involved in balance, taste, hearing, and control of muscles of the face and neck.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] The next structure rostral to the medulla is the pons, which lies on the ventral anterior side of the brainstem.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] Nuclei in the pons include pontine nuclei which work with the cerebellum and transmit information between the cerebellum and the cerebral cortex.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] In the dorsal posterior pons lie nuclei that are involved in the functions of breathing, sleep, and taste.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] The midbrain, or mesencephalon, is situated above and rostral to the pons.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] It includes nuclei linking distinct parts of the motor system, including the cerebellum, the basal ganglia and both cerebral hemispheres, among others.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] Additionally, parts of the visual and auditory systems are located in the midbrain, including control of automatic eye movements.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] The brainstem at large provides entry and exit to the brain for a number of pathways for motor and autonomic control of the face and neck through cranial nerves, Autonomic control of the organs is mediated by the tenth cranial nerve.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] A large portion of the brainstem is involved in such autonomic control of the body.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] Such functions may engage the heart, blood vessels, and pupils, among others.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] The brainstem also holds the reticular formation, a group of nuclei involved in both arousal and alertness.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] The cerebellum is composed of several dividing fissures and lobes.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] Its function includes the control of posture and the coordination of movements of parts of the body, including the eyes and head, as well as the limbs.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] Further, it is involved in motion that has been learned and perfected through practice, and it will adapt to new learned movements.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] Despite its previous classification as a motor structure, the cerebellum also displays connections to areas of the cerebral cortex involved in language and cognition.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] These connections have been shown by the use of medical imaging techniques, such as functional MRI and Positron emission tomography.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] The body of the cerebellum holds more neurons than any other structure of the brain, including that of the larger cerebrum, but is also more extensively understood than other structures of the brain, as it includes fewer types of different neurons.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] It handles and processes sensory stimuli, motor information, as well as balance information from the vestibular organ.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] The two structures of the diencephalon worth noting are the thalamus and the hypothalamus.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] The thalamus acts as a linkage between incoming pathways from the peripheral nervous system as well as the optical nerve (though it does not receive input from the olfactory nerve) to the cerebral hemispheres.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] Previously it was considered only a "relay station", but it is engaged in the sorting of information that will reach cerebral hemispheres (neocortex).
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] Apart from its function of sorting information from the periphery, the thalamus also connects the cerebellum and basal ganglia with the cerebrum.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] In common with the aforementioned reticular system the thalamus is involved in wakefulness and consciousness, such as though the SCN.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] The hypothalamus engages in functions of a number of primitive emotions or feelings such as hunger, thirst and maternal bonding.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] This is regulated partly through control of secretion of hormones from the pituitary gland.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] Additionally the hypothalamus plays a role in motivation and many other behaviors of the individual.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] The cerebrum of cerebral hemispheres make up the largest visual portion of the human brain.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] Various structures combine to form the cerebral hemispheres, among others: the cortex, basal ganglia, amygdala and hippocampus.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] The hemispheres together control a large portion of the functions of the human brain such as emotion, memory, perception and motor functions.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] Apart from this the cerebral hemispheres stand for the cognitive capabilities of the brain.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] Connecting each of the hemispheres is the corpus callosum as well as several additional commissures.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] One of the most important parts of the cerebral hemispheres is the cortex, made up of gray matter covering the surface of the brain.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] Functionally, the cerebral cortex is involved in planning and carrying out of everyday tasks.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] The hippocampus is involved in storage of memories, the amygdala plays a role in perception and communication of emotion, while the basal ganglia play a major role in the coordination of voluntary movement.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] The PNS consists of neurons, axons, and Schwann cells.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] Oligodendrocytes and Schwann cells have similar functions in the CNS and PNS, respectively.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] Both act to add myelin sheaths to the axons, which acts as a form of insulation allowing for better and faster proliferation of electrical signals along the nerves.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] Axons in the CNS are often very short, barely a few millimeters, and do not need the same degree of isolation as peripheral nerves.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] Some peripheral nerves can be over 1 meter in length, such as the nerves to the big toe.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] To ensure signals move at sufficient speed, myelination is needed.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] The way in which the Schwann cells and oligodendrocytes myelinate nerves differ.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] A Schwann cell usually myelinates a single axon, completely surrounding it.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] Sometimes, they may myelinate many axons, especially when in areas of short axons.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] Oligodendrocytes usually myelinate several axons.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] They do this by sending out thin projections of their cell membrane, which envelop and enclose the axon.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] Top image: CNS as seen in a median section of a 5-week-old embryo.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] Bottom image: CNS seen in a median section of a 3-month-old embryo.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] During early development of the vertebrate embryo, a longitudinal groove on the neural plate gradually deepens and the ridges on either side of the groove (the neural folds) become elevated, and ultimately meet, transforming the groove into a closed tube called the neural tube.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] The formation of the neural tube is called neurulation.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] At this stage, the walls of the neural tube contain proliferating neural stem cells in a region called the ventricular zone.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] The neural stem cells, principally radial glial cells, multiply and generate neurons through the process of neurogenesis, forming the rudiment of the CNS.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] The neural tube gives rise to both brain and spinal cord.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] The anterior (or 'rostral') portion of the neural tube initially differentiates into three brain vesicles (pockets): the prosencephalon at the front, the mesencephalon, and, between the mesencephalon and the spinal cord, the rhombencephalon.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] (By six weeks in the human embryo) the prosencephalon then divides further into the telencephalon and diencephalon; and the rhombencephalon divides into the metencephalon and myelencephalon.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] The spinal cord is derived from the posterior or 'caudal' portion of the neural tube.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] As a vertebrate grows, these vesicles differentiate further still.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] The telencephalon differentiates into, among other things, the striatum, the hippocampus and the neocortex, and its cavity becomes the first and second ventricles (lateral ventricles).
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] Diencephalon elaborations include the subthalamus, hypothalamus, thalamus and epithalamus, and its cavity forms the third ventricle.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] The tectum, pretectum, cerebral peduncle and other structures develop out of the mesencephalon, and its cavity grows into the mesencephalic duct (cerebral aqueduct).
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] The metencephalon becomes, among other things, the pons and the cerebellum, the myelencephalon forms the medulla oblongata, and their cavities develop into the fourth ventricle.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] , regarded an archetypal vertebrate, lacking a true brain.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] Bottom: spindle diagram of the evolution of vertebrates.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] Planarians, members of the phylum Platyhelminthes (flatworms), have the simplest, clearly defined delineation of a nervous system into a CNS and a PNS.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] Their primitive brains, consisting of two fused anterior ganglia, and longitudinal nerve cords form the CNS.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] Like vertebrates, have a distinct CNS and PNS.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] The nerves projecting laterally from the CNS form their PNS.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] A molecular study found that more than 95% of the 116 genes involved in the nervous system of planarians, which includes genes related to the CNS, also exist in humans.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] In arthropods, the ventral nerve cord, the subesophageal ganglia and the supraesophageal ganglia are usually seen as making up the CNS.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] Arthropoda, unlike vertebrates, have inhibitory motor neurons due to their small size.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] The CNS of chordates differs from that of other animals in being placed dorsally in the body, above the gut and notochord/spine.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] The basic pattern of the CNS is highly conserved throughout the different species of vertebrates and during evolution.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] The major trend that can be observed is towards a progressive telencephalisation: the telencephalon of reptiles is only an appendix to the large olfactory bulb, while in mammals it makes up most of the volume of the CNS.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] In the human brain, the telencephalon covers most of the diencephalon and the entire mesencephalon.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] Indeed, the allometric study of brain size among different species shows a striking continuity from rats to whales, and allows us to complete the knowledge about the evolution of the CNS obtained through cranial endocasts.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] Mammals – which appear in the fossil record after the first fishes, amphibians, and reptiles – are the only vertebrates to possess the evolutionarily recent, outermost part of the cerebral cortex (main part of the telencephalon excluding olfactory bulb) known as the neocortex.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] This part of the brain is, in mammals, involved in higher thinking and further processing of all senses in the sensory cortices (processing for smell was previously only done by its bulb while those for non-smell senses were only done by the tectum).
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] The neocortex of monotremes (the duck-billed platypus and several species of spiny anteaters) and of marsupials (such as kangaroos, koalas, opossums, wombats, and Tasmanian devils) lack the convolutions – gyri and sulci – found in the neocortex of most placental mammals (eutherians).
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] Within placental mammals, the size and complexity of the neocortex increased over time.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] The area of the neocortex of mice is only about 1/100 that of monkeys, and that of monkeys is only about 1/10 that of humans.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] In addition, rats lack convolutions in their neocortex (possibly also because rats are small mammals), whereas cats have a moderate degree of convolutions, and humans have quite extensive convolutions.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] Extreme convolution of the neocortex is found in dolphins, possibly related to their complex echolocation.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] Lastly, cancers of the central nervous system can cause severe illness and, when malignant, can have very high mortality rates.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] Symptoms depend on the size, growth rate, location and malignancy of tumors and can include alterations in motor control, hearing loss, headaches and changes in cognitive ability and autonomic functioning.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/central-nervous-system] Specialty professional organizations recommend that neurological imaging of the brain be done only to answer a specific clinical question and not as routine screening.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] In biology, the **nervous system** is the highly complex part of an animal that coordinates its actions and sensory information by transmitting signals to and from different parts of its body.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] The nervous system detects environmental changes that impact the body, then works in tandem with the endocrine system to respond to such events.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] Nervous tissue first arose in wormlike organisms about 550 to 600 million years ago.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] In vertebrates, it consists of two main parts, the central nervous system (CNS) and the peripheral nervous system (PNS).
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] The CNS consists of the brain and spinal cord.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] The PNS consists mainly of nerves, which are enclosed bundles of long fibers, or axons, that connect the CNS to every other part of the body.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] Nerves that transmit signals from the brain are called motor nerves (efferent), while those nerves that transmit information from the body to the CNS are called sensory nerves (afferent).
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] The PNS is divided into two separate subsystems, the somatic and autonomic nervous systems.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] The autonomic nervous system is further subdivided into the sympathetic, parasympathetic and enteric nervous systems.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] The sympathetic nervous system is activated in cases of emergencies to mobilize energy, while the parasympathetic nervous system is activated when organisms are in a relaxed state.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] The enteric nervous system functions to control the gastrointestinal system.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] Nerves that exit from the brain are called cranial nerves while those exiting from the spinal cord are called spinal nerves.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] The nervous system consists of nervous tissue which, at a cellular level, is defined by the presence of a special type of cell, called the neuron.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] Neurons have special structures that allow them to send signals rapidly and precisely to other cells.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] They send these signals in the form of electrochemical impulses traveling along thin fibers called axons, which can be directly transmitted to neighboring cells through electrical synapses or cause chemicals called neurotransmitters to be released at chemical synapses.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] A cell that receives a synaptic signal from a neuron may be excited, inhibited, or otherwise modulated.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] The connections between neurons can form neural pathways, neural circuits, and larger networks that generate an organism's perception of the world and determine its behavior.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] Along with neurons, the nervous system contains other specialized cells called glial cells (or simply glia), which provide structural and metabolic support.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] Many of the cells and vasculature channels within the nervous system make up the neurovascular unit, which regulates cerebral blood flow in order to rapidly satisfy the high energy demands of activated neurons.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] Nervous systems are found in most multicellular animals, but vary greatly in complexity.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] The only multicellular animals that have no nervous system at all are sponges, placozoans, and mesozoans, which have very simple body plans.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] The nervous systems of the radially symmetric organisms ctenophores (comb jellies) and cnidarians (which include anemones, hydras, corals and jellyfish) consist of a diffuse nerve net.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] All other animal species, with the exception of a few types of worm, have a nervous system containing a brain, a central cord (or two cords running in parallel), and nerves radiating from the brain and central cord.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] The size of the nervous system ranges from a few hundred cells in the simplest worms, to around 300 billion cells in African elephants.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] The central nervous system functions to send signals from one cell to others, or from one part of the body to others and to receive feedback.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] Malfunction of the nervous system can occur as a result of genetic defects, physical damage due to trauma or toxicity, infection, or simply senescence.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] The medical specialty of neurology studies disorders of the nervous system and looks for interventions that can prevent or treat them.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] In the peripheral nervous system, the most common problem is the failure of nerve conduction, which can be due to different causes including diabetic neuropathy and demyelinating disorders such as multiple sclerosis and amyotrophic lateral sclerosis.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] Neuroscience is the field of science that focuses on the study of the nervous system.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] The nervous system derives its name from nerves, which are cylindrical bundles of fibers (the axons of neurons), that emanate from the brain and spinal cord, and branch repeatedly to innervate every part of the body.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] Nerves are large enough to have been recognized by the ancient Egyptians, Greeks, and Romans, but their internal structure was not understood until it became possible to examine them using a microscope.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] A microscopic examination shows that nerves consist primarily of axons, along with different membranes that wrap around them and segregate them into fascicles.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] The neurons that give rise to nerves do not lie entirely within the nerves themselves—their cell bodies reside within the brain, spinal cord, or peripheral ganglia.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] All animals more advanced than sponges have nervous systems.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] However, even sponges, unicellular animals, and non-animals such as slime molds have cell-to-cell signalling mechanisms that are precursors to those of neurons.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] In radially symmetric animals such as the jellyfish and hydra, the nervous system consists of a nerve net, a diffuse network of isolated cells.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] In bilaterian animals, which make up the great majority of existing species, the nervous system has a common structure that originated early in the Ediacaran period, over 550 million years ago.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] The nervous system contains two main categories or types of cells: neurons and glial cells.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] The nervous system is defined by the presence of a special type of cell—the neuron (sometimes called "neurone" or "nerve cell").
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] Many types of neuron possess an axon, a protoplasmic protrusion that can extend to distant parts of the body and make thousands of synaptic contacts; axons typically extend throughout the body in bundles called nerves.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] Even in the nervous system of a single species such as humans, hundreds of different types of neurons exist, with a wide variety of morphologies and functions.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] Glial cells (named from the Greek for "glue") are non-neuronal cells that provide support and nutrition, maintain homeostasis, form myelin, and participate in signal transmission in the nervous system.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] In the human brain, it is estimated that the total number of glia roughly equals the number of neurons, although the proportions vary in different brain areas.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] Among the most important functions of glial cells are to support neurons and hold them in place; to supply nutrients to neurons; to insulate neurons electrically; to destroy pathogens and remove dead neurons; and to provide guidance cues directing the axons of neurons to their targets.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] Recent findings indicate that glial cells, such as microglia and astrocytes, serve as important resident immune cells within the central nervous system.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] The nervous system of vertebrates (including humans) is divided into the central nervous system (CNS) and the peripheral nervous system (PNS).
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] The CNS is the major division, and consists of the brain and the spinal cord.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] The spinal canal contains the spinal cord, while the cranial cavity contains the brain.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] The CNS is enclosed and protected by the meninges, a three-layered system of membranes, including a tough, leathery outer layer called the dura mater.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] The brain is also protected by the skull, and the spinal cord by the vertebrae.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] The peripheral nervous system (PNS) is a collective term for the nervous system structures that do not lie within the CNS.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] The large majority of the axon bundles called nerves are considered to belong to the PNS, even when the cell bodies of the neurons to which they belong reside within the brain or spinal cord.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] The PNS is divided into somatic and visceral parts.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] The somatic part consists of the nerves that innervate the skin, joints, and muscles.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] The cell bodies of somatic sensory neurons lie in dorsal root ganglia of the spinal cord.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] The visceral part, also known as the autonomic nervous system, contains neurons that innervate the internal organs, blood vessels, and glands.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] The autonomic nervous system itself consists of two parts: the sympathetic nervous system and the parasympathetic nervous system.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] Some authors also include sensory neurons whose cell bodies lie in the periphery (for senses such as hearing) as part of the PNS; others, however, omit them.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] The vertebrate nervous system can also be divided into areas called gray matter and white matter.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] Gray matter (which is only gray in preserved tissue, and is better described as pink or light brown in living tissue) contains a high proportion of cell bodies of neurons.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] White matter is composed mainly of myelinated axons, and takes its color from the myelin.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] White matter includes all of the nerves, and much of the interior of the brain and spinal cord.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] Gray matter is found in clusters of neurons in the brain and spinal cord, and in cortical layers that line their surfaces.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] There is an anatomical convention that a cluster of neurons in the brain or spinal cord is called a nucleus, whereas a cluster of neurons in the periphery is called a ganglion.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] There are, however, a few exceptions to this rule, notably including the part of the forebrain called the basal ganglia.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] Sponges have no cells connected to each other by synaptic junctions, that is, no neurons, and therefore no nervous system.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] They do, however, have homologs of many genes that play key roles in synaptic function.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] Recent studies have shown that sponge cells express a group of proteins that cluster together to form a structure resembling a postsynaptic density (the signal-receiving part of a synapse).
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] However, the function of this structure is currently unclear.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] Although sponge cells do not show synaptic transmission, they do communicate with each other via calcium waves and other impulses, which mediate some simple actions such as whole-body contraction.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] Jellyfish, comb jellies, and related animals have diffuse nerve nets rather than a central nervous system.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] In most jellyfish the nerve net is spread more or less evenly across the body; in comb jellies it is concentrated near the mouth.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] In some cases groups of intermediate neurons are clustered into discrete ganglia.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] The development of the nervous system in radiata is relatively unstructured.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] Unlike bilaterians, radiata only have two primordial cell layers, endoderm and ectoderm.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] Neurons are generated from a special set of ectodermal precursor cells, which also serve as precursors for every other ectodermal cell type.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] The vast majority of existing animals are bilaterians, meaning animals with left and right sides that are approximate mirror images of each other.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] All bilateria are thought to have descended from a common wormlike ancestor that appear as fossils beginning in the Ediacaran period, 550–600 million years ago.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] The fundamental bilaterian body form is a tube with a hollow gut cavity running from mouth to anus, and a nerve cord with an enlargement (a "ganglion") for each body segment, with an especially large ganglion at the front, called the "brain".
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] Even mammals, including humans, show the segmented bilaterian body plan at the level of the nervous system.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] The spinal cord contains a series of segmental ganglia, each giving rise to motor and sensory nerves that innervate a portion of the body surface and underlying musculature.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] On the limbs, the layout of the innervation pattern is complex, but on the trunk it gives rise to a series of narrow bands.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] The top three segments belong to the brain, giving rise to the forebrain, midbrain, and hindbrain.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] Bilaterians can be divided, based on events that occur very early in embryonic development, into two groups (superphyla) called protostomes and deuterostomes.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] Deuterostomes include vertebrates as well as echinoderms, hemichordates (mainly acorn worms), and Xenoturbellidans.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] Protostomes, the more diverse group, include arthropods, molluscs, and numerous phyla of "worms".
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] There is a basic difference between the two groups in the placement of the nervous system within the body: protostomes possess a nerve cord on the ventral (usually bottom) side of the body, whereas in deuterostomes the nerve cord is on the dorsal (usually top) side.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] In fact, numerous aspects of the body are inverted between the two groups, including the expression patterns of several genes that show dorsal-to-ventral gradients.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] Most anatomists now consider that the bodies of protostomes and deuterostomes are "flipped over" with respect to each other, a hypothesis that was first proposed by Geoffroy Saint-Hilaire for insects in comparison to vertebrates.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] Thus insects, for example, have nerve cords that run along the ventral midline of the body, while all vertebrates have spinal cords that run along the dorsal midline.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] Worms are the simplest bilaterian animals, and reveal the basic structure of the bilaterian nervous system in the most straightforward way.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] As an example, earthworms have dual nerve cords running along the length of the body and merging at the tail and the mouth.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] These nerve cords are connected by transverse nerves like the rungs of a ladder.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] These transverse nerves help coordinate the two sides of the animal.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] Two ganglia at the head (the "nerve ring") end function similar to a simple brain.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] Photoreceptors on the animal's eyespots provide sensory information on light and dark.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] The nervous system of one very small roundworm, the nematode *Caenorhabditis elegans*, has been completely mapped out in a connectome including its synapses.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] Every neuron and its cellular lineage has been recorded and most, if not all, of the neural connections are known.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] In this species, the nervous system is sexually dimorphic; the nervous systems of the two sexes, males and female hermaphrodites, have different numbers of neurons and groups of neurons that perform sex-specific functions.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] In *C. elegans*, males have exactly 383 neurons, while hermaphrodites have exactly 302 neurons.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] Arthropods, such as insects and crustaceans, have a nervous system made up of a series of ganglia, connected by a ventral nerve cord made up of two parallel connectives running along the length of the belly.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] Typically, each body segment has one ganglion on each side, though some ganglia are fused to form the brain and other large ganglia.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] The head segment contains the brain, also known as the supraesophageal ganglion.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] In the insect nervous system, the brain is anatomically divided into the protocerebrum, deutocerebrum, and tritocerebrum.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] Immediately behind the brain is the subesophageal ganglion, which is composed of three pairs of fused ganglia.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] It controls the mouthparts, the salivary glands and certain muscles.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] Many arthropods have well-developed sensory organs, including compound eyes for vision and antennae for olfaction and pheromone sensation.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] The sensory information from these organs is processed by the brain.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] In insects, many neurons have cell bodies that are positioned at the edge of the brain and are electrically passive—the cell bodies serve only to provide metabolic support and do not participate in signalling.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] A protoplasmic fiber runs from the cell body and branches profusely, with some parts transmitting signals and other parts receiving signals.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] Thus, most parts of the insect brain have passive cell bodies arranged around the periphery, while the neural signal processing takes place in a tangle of protoplasmic fibers called neuropil, in the interior.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] The cephalic molluscs have two pairs of main nerve cords organized around a number of paired ganglia, the visceral cords serving the internal organs and the pedal ones serving the foot.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] Most pairs of corresponding ganglia on both sides of the body are linked by commissures (relatively large bundles of nerves).
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] The ganglia above the gut are the cerebral, the pleural, and the visceral, which are located above the esophagus (gullet).
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] The pedal ganglia, which control the foot, are below the esophagus and their commissure and connectives to the cerebral and pleural ganglia surround the esophagus in a circumesophageal nerve ring or *nerve collar*.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] The acephalic molluscs (i.e., bivalves) also have this ring but it is less obvious and less important.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] The bivalves have only three pairs of ganglia—cerebral, pedal, and visceral—with the visceral as the largest and most important of the three functioning as the principal center of "thinking".
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] Some such as the scallops have eyes around the edges of their shells which connect to a pair of looped nerves and which provide the ability to distinguish between light and shadow.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] In vertebrate nervous systems very few neurons are "identified" in this sense—in humans, there are believed to be none—but in simpler nervous systems, some or all neurons may be thus unique.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] In the roundworm *C. elegans*, whose nervous system is the most thoroughly described of any animal's, every neuron in the body is uniquely identifiable, with the same location and the same connections in every individual worm.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] One notable consequence of this fact is that the form of the *C. elegans* nervous system is completely specified by the genome, with no experience-dependent plasticity.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] The brains of many molluscs and insects also contain substantial numbers of identified neurons.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] In vertebrates, the best known identified neurons are the gigantic Mauthner cells of fish.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] Every fish has two Mauthner cells, in the bottom part of the brainstem, one on the left side and one on the right.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] Each Mauthner cell has an axon that crosses over, innervating neurons at the same brain level and then travelling down through the spinal cord, making numerous connections as it goes.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] The synapses generated by a Mauthner cell are so powerful that a single action potential gives rise to a major behavioral response: within milliseconds the fish curves its body into a C-shape, then straightens, thereby propelling itself rapidly forward.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] Functionally this is a fast escape response, triggered most easily by a strong sound wave or pressure wave impinging on the lateral line organ of the fish.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] Mauthner cells are not the only identified neurons in fish—there are about 20 more types, including pairs of "Mauthner cell analogs" in each spinal segmental nucleus.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] Although a Mauthner cell is capable of bringing about an escape response individually, in the context of ordinary behavior other types of cells usually contribute to shaping the amplitude and direction of the response.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] Mauthner cells have been described as command neurons.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] A command neuron is a special type of identified neuron, defined as a neuron that is capable of driving a specific behavior individually.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] Such neurons appear most commonly in the fast escape systems of various species—the squid giant axon and squid giant synapse, used for pioneering experiments in neurophysiology because of their enormous size, both participate in the fast escape circuit of the squid.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] The concept of a command neuron has, however, become controversial, because of studies showing that some neurons that initially appeared to fit the description were really only capable of evoking a response in a limited set of circumstances.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] At the most basic level, the function of the nervous system is to send signals from one cell to others, or from one part of the body to others.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] There are multiple ways that a cell can send signals to other cells.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] One is by releasing chemicals called hormones into the internal circulation, so that they can diffuse to distant sites.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] In contrast to this "broadcast" mode of signaling, the nervous system provides "point-to-point" signals—neurons project their axons to specific target areas and make synaptic connections with specific target cells.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] Thus, neural signaling is capable of a much higher level of specificity than hormonal signaling.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] It is also much faster: the fastest nerve signals travel at speeds that exceed 100 meters per second.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] At a more integrative level, the primary function of the nervous system is to control the body.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] The evolution of a complex nervous system has made it possible for various animal species to have advanced perception abilities such as vision, complex social interactions, rapid coordination of organ systems, and integrated processing of concurrent signals.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] In humans, the sophistication of the nervous system makes it possible to have language, abstract representation of concepts, transmission of culture, and many other features of human society that would not exist without the human brain.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] Most neurons send signals via their axons, although some types are capable of dendrite-to-dendrite communication.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] Electrical synapses make direct electrical connections between neurons, but chemical synapses are much more common, and much more diverse in function.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] At a chemical synapse, the cell that sends signals is called presynaptic, and the cell that receives signals is called postsynaptic.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] Both the presynaptic and postsynaptic areas are full of molecular machinery that carries out the signalling process.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] The presynaptic area contains large numbers of tiny spherical vessels called synaptic vesicles, packed with neurotransmitter chemicals.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] When the presynaptic terminal is electrically stimulated, an array of molecules embedded in the membrane are activated, and cause the contents of the vesicles to be released into the narrow space between the presynaptic and postsynaptic membranes, called the synaptic cleft.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] The neurotransmitter then binds to receptors embedded in the postsynaptic membrane, causing them to enter an activated state.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] Depending on the type of receptor, the resulting effect on the postsynaptic cell may be excitatory, inhibitory, or modulatory in more complex ways.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] For example, release of the neurotransmitter acetylcholine at a synaptic contact between a motor neuron and a muscle cell induces rapid contraction of the muscle cell.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] The entire synaptic transmission process takes only a fraction of a millisecond, although the effects on the postsynaptic cell may last much longer (even indefinitely, in cases where the synaptic signal leads to the formation of a memory trace).
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] There are literally hundreds of different types of synapses.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] In fact, there are over a hundred known neurotransmitters, and many of them have multiple types of receptors.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] Many synapses use more than one neurotransmitter—a common arrangement is for a synapse to use one fast-acting small-molecule neurotransmitter such as glutamate or GABA, along with one or more peptide neurotransmitters that play slower-acting modulatory roles.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] Molecular neuroscientists generally divide receptors into two broad groups: chemically gated ion channels and second messenger systems.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] When a chemically gated ion channel is activated, it forms a passage that allows specific types of ions to flow across the membrane.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] Depending on the type of ion, the effect on the target cell may be excitatory or inhibitory.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] When a second messenger system is activated, it starts a cascade of molecular interactions inside the target cell, which may ultimately produce a wide variety of complex effects, such as increasing or decreasing the sensitivity of the cell to stimuli, or even altering gene transcription.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] According to a rule called Dale's principle, which has only a few known exceptions, a neuron releases the same neurotransmitters at all of its synapses.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] This does not mean, though, that a neuron exerts the same effect on all of its targets, because the effect of a synapse depends not on the neurotransmitter, but on the receptors that it activates.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] Because different targets can (and frequently do) use different types of receptors, it is possible for a neuron to have excitatory effects on one set of target cells, inhibitory effects on others, and complex modulatory effects on others still.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] Nevertheless, it happens that the two most widely used neurotransmitters, glutamate and GABA, each have largely consistent effects.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] Glutamate has several widely occurring types of receptors, but all of them are excitatory or modulatory.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] Similarly, GABA has several widely occurring receptor types, but all of them are inhibitory.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] Because of this consistency, glutamatergic cells are frequently referred to as "excitatory neurons", and GABAergic cells as "inhibitory neurons".
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] Strictly speaking, this is an abuse of terminology—it is the receptors that are excitatory and inhibitory, not the neurons—but it is commonly seen even in scholarly publications.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] One very important subset of synapses are capable of forming memory traces by means of long-lasting activity-dependent changes in synaptic strength.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] The best-known form of neural memory is a process called long-term potentiation (abbreviated LTP), which operates at synapses that use the neurotransmitter glutamate acting on a special type of receptor known as the NMDA receptor.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] The NMDA receptor has an "associative" property: if the two cells involved in the synapse are both activated at approximately the same time, a channel opens that permits calcium to flow into the target cell.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] The calcium entry initiates a second messenger cascade that ultimately leads to an increase in the number of glutamate receptors in the target cell, thereby increasing the effective strength of the synapse.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] This change in strength can last for weeks or longer.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] Since the discovery of LTP in 1973, many other types of synaptic memory traces have been found, involving increases or decreases in synaptic strength that are induced by varying conditions, and last for variable periods of time.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] The reward system, that reinforces desired behaviour for example, depends on a variant form of LTP that is conditioned on an extra input coming from a reward-signalling pathway that uses dopamine as neurotransmitter.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] All these forms of synaptic modifiability, taken collectively, give rise to neural plasticity, that is, to a capability for the nervous system to adapt itself to variations in the environment.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] The basic neuronal function of sending signals to other cells includes a capability for neurons to exchange signals with each other.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] Networks formed by interconnected groups of neurons are capable of a wide variety of functions, including feature detection, pattern generation and timing, and there are seen to be countless types of information processing possible.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] Warren McCulloch and Walter Pitts showed in 1943 that even artificial neural networks formed from a greatly simplified mathematical abstraction of a neuron are capable of universal computation.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] Historically, for many years the predominant view of the function of the nervous system was as a stimulus-response associator.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] In this conception, neural processing begins with stimuli that activate sensory neurons, producing signals that propagate through chains of connections in the spinal cord and brain, giving rise eventually to activation of motor neurons and thereby to muscle contraction, i.e., to overt responses.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] Descartes believed that all of the behaviors of animals, and most of the behaviors of humans, could be explained in terms of stimulus-response circuits, although he also believed that higher cognitive functions such as language were not capable of being explained mechanistically.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] Neurons were found to be capable of producing regular sequences of action potentials, or sequences of bursts, even in complete isolation.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] When intrinsically active neurons are connected to each other in complex circuits, the possibilities for generating intricate temporal patterns become far more extensive.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] A modern conception views the function of the nervous system partly in terms of stimulus-response chains, and partly in terms of intrinsically generated activity patterns—both types of activity interact with each other to generate the full repertoire of behavior.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] The simplest type of neural circuit is a reflex arc, which begins with a sensory input and ends with a motor output, passing through a sequence of neurons connected in series.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] This can be shown in the "withdrawal reflex" causing a hand to jerk back after a hot stove is touched.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] The circuit begins with sensory receptors in the skin that are activated by harmful levels of heat: a special type of molecular structure embedded in the membrane causes heat to change the electrical field across the membrane.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] If the change in electrical potential is large enough to pass the given threshold, it evokes an action potential, which is transmitted along the axon of the receptor cell, into the spinal cord.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] There the axon makes excitatory synaptic contacts with other cells, some of which project (send axonal output) to the same region of the spinal cord, others projecting into the brain.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] One target is a set of spinal interneurons that project to motor neurons controlling the arm muscles.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] The interneurons excite the motor neurons, and if the excitation is strong enough, some of the motor neurons generate action potentials, which travel down their axons to the point where they make excitatory synaptic contacts with muscle cells.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] The excitatory signals induce contraction of the muscle cells, which causes the joint angles in the arm to change, pulling the arm away.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] In reality, this straightforward schema is subject to numerous complications.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] Although for the simplest reflexes there are short neural paths from sensory neuron to motor neuron, there are also other nearby neurons that participate in the circuit and modulate the response.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] Furthermore, there are projections from the brain to the spinal cord that are capable of enhancing or inhibiting the reflex.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] Although the simplest reflexes may be mediated by circuits lying entirely within the spinal cord, more complex responses rely on signal processing in the brain.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] For example, when an object in the periphery of the visual field moves, and a person looks toward it many stages of signal processing are initiated.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] The initial sensory response, in the retina of the eye, and the final motor response, in the oculomotor nuclei of the brainstem, are not all that different from those in a simple reflex, but the intermediate stages are completely different.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] Instead of a one or two step chain of processing, the visual signals pass through perhaps a dozen stages of integration, involving the thalamus, cerebral cortex, basal ganglia, superior colliculus, cerebellum, and several brainstem nuclei.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] These areas perform signal-processing functions that include feature detection, perceptual analysis, memory recall, decision-making, and motor planning.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] Feature detection is the ability to extract biologically relevant information from combinations of sensory signals.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] In the visual system, for example, sensory receptors in the retina of the eye are only individually capable of detecting "points of light" in the outside world.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] Second-level visual neurons receive input from groups of primary receptors, higher-level neurons receive input from groups of second-level neurons, and so on, forming a hierarchy of processing stages.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] At each stage, important information is extracted from the signal ensemble and unimportant information is discarded.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] By the end of the process, input signals representing "points of light" have been transformed into a neural representation of objects in the surrounding world and their properties.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] The most sophisticated sensory processing occurs inside the brain, but complex feature extraction also takes place in the spinal cord and in peripheral sensory organs such as the retina.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] Although stimulus-response mechanisms are the easiest to understand, the nervous system is also capable of controlling the body in ways that do not require an external stimulus, by means of internally generated rhythms of activity.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] Because of the variety of voltage-sensitive ion channels that can be embedded in the membrane of a neuron, many types of neurons are capable, even in isolation, of generating rhythmic sequences of action potentials, or rhythmic alternations between high-rate bursting and quiescence.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] When neurons that are intrinsically rhythmic are connected to each other by excitatory or inhibitory synapses, the resulting networks are capable of a wide variety of dynamical behaviors, including attractor dynamics, periodicity, and even chaos.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] A network of neurons that uses its internal structure to generate temporally structured output, without requiring a corresponding temporally structured stimulus, is called a central pattern generator.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] Internal pattern generation operates on a wide range of time scales, from milliseconds to hours or longer.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] One of the most important types of temporal pattern is circadian rhythmicity—that is, rhythmicity with a period of approximately 24 hours.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] All animals that have been studied show circadian fluctuations in neural activity, which control circadian alternations in behavior such as the sleep-wake cycle.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] Experimental studies dating from the 1990s have shown that circadian rhythms are generated by a "genetic clock" consisting of a special set of genes whose expression level rises and falls over the course of the day.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] Animals as diverse as insects and vertebrates share a similar genetic clock system.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] The circadian clock is influenced by light but continues to operate even when light levels are held constant and no other external time-of-day cues are available.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] The clock genes are expressed in many parts of the nervous system as well as many peripheral organs, but in mammals, all of these "tissue clocks" are kept in synchrony by signals that emanate from a master timekeeper in a tiny part of the brain called the suprachiasmatic nucleus.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] A mirror neuron is a neuron that fires both when an animal acts and when the animal observes the same action performed by another.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] Thus, the neuron "mirrors" the behavior of the other, as though the observer were itself acting.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] Such neurons have been directly observed in primate species.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] Birds have been shown to have imitative resonance behaviors and neurological evidence suggests the presence of some form of mirroring system.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] In humans, brain activity consistent with that of mirror neurons has been found in the premotor cortex, the supplementary motor area, the primary somatosensory cortex and the inferior parietal cortex.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] The function of the mirror system is a subject of much speculation, with some scientists cautioning that the claims being made for the role of mirror neurons are not supported by adequate research.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] Researchers in cognitive neuroscience and cognitive psychology consider that this system provides the physiological mechanism for the perception/action coupling (see the common coding theory).
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] They argue that mirror neurons may be important for understanding the actions of other people, and for learning new skills by imitation.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] Some researchers also speculate that mirror systems may simulate observed actions, and thus contribute to theory of mind skills, while others relate mirror neurons to language abilities.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] Another position explains limited cases of interpersonal dynamics in which mirror neurons are observed in which mirror neurons can be found in interpersonal dynamics that correspond to the mother-fetus neurocognitive model.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] The proposed local neuronal oscillations of two nervous systems are synchronized through interference with the low-frequency electromagnetic field of the mother's heart.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] Therefore, the fetal nervous system learns to react in the same way as the mother's nervous system responds to stimuli.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] However, no widely accepted neural or computational models exist to describe how mirror neuron activity supports cognitive functions, such as imitation.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] All bilaterian animals at an early stage of development form a gastrula, which is polarized, with one end called the animal pole and the other the vegetal pole.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] In vertebrates, the first sign of the nervous system is the appearance of a thin strip of cells along the center of the back, called the neural plate.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] The inner portion of the neural plate (along the midline) is destined to become the central nervous system (CNS), the outer portion the peripheral nervous system (PNS).
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] As development proceeds, a fold called the neural groove appears along the midline.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] This fold deepens, and then closes up at the top.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] At this point the future CNS appears as a cylindrical structure called the neural tube, whereas the future PNS appears as two strips of tissue called the neural crest, running lengthwise above the neural tube.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] The sequence of stages from neural plate to neural tube and neural crest is known as neurulation.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] In the early 20th century, a set of famous experiments by Hans Spemann and Hilde Mangold showed that the formation of nervous tissue is "induced" by signals from a group of mesodermal cells called the *organizer region*.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] For decades, though, the nature of neural induction defeated every attempt to figure it out, until finally it was resolved by genetic approaches in the 1990s.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] Induction of neural tissue requires inhibition of the gene for a so-called bone morphogenetic protein, or BMP.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] Specifically the protein BMP4 appears to be involved.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] Two proteins called Noggin and Chordin, both secreted by the mesoderm, are capable of inhibiting BMP4 and thereby inducing ectoderm to turn into neural tissue.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] It appears that a similar molecular mechanism is involved for widely disparate types of animals, including arthropods as well as vertebrates.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] In some animals, however, another type of molecule called Fibroblast Growth Factor or FGF may also play an important role in induction.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] Induction of neural tissues causes formation of neural precursor cells, called neuroblasts.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] In *Drosophila*, neuroblasts divide asymmetrically, so that one product is a "ganglion mother cell" (GMC), and the other is a neuroblast.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] A GMC divides once, to give rise to either a pair of neurons or a pair of glial cells.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] In all, a neuroblast is capable of generating an indefinite number of neurons or glia.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] As shown in a 2008 study, one factor common to all bilateral organisms (including humans) is a family of secreted signaling molecules called neurotrophins which regulate the growth and survival of neurons.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] Zhu et al. identified DNT1, the first neurotrophin found in flies.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] DNT1 shares structural similarity with all known neurotrophins and is a key factor in the fate of neurons in *Drosophila*.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] Because neurotrophins have now been identified in both vertebrate and invertebrates, this evidence suggests that neurotrophins were present in an ancestor common to bilateral organisms and may represent a common mechanism for nervous system formation.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] The central nervous system is protected by major physical and chemical barriers.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] Physically, the brain and spinal cord are surrounded by tough meningeal membranes, and enclosed in the bones of the skull and vertebral column, which combine to form a strong physical shield.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] Chemically, the brain and spinal cord are isolated by the blood–brain barrier, which prevents most types of chemicals from moving from the bloodstream into the interior of the CNS.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] These protections make the CNS less susceptible in many ways than the PNS; the flip side, however, is that damage to the CNS tends to have more serious consequences.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] Although nerves tend to lie deep under the skin except in a few places such as the ulnar nerve near the elbow joint, they are still relatively exposed to physical damage, which can cause pain, loss of sensation, or loss of muscle control.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] Damage to nerves can also be caused by swelling or bruises at places where a nerve passes through a tight bony channel, as happens in carpal tunnel syndrome.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] If a nerve is completely transected, it will often regenerate, but for long nerves this process may take months to complete.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] Many cases have no cause that can be identified, and are referred to as idiopathic.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] It is also possible for nerves to lose function temporarily, resulting in numbness as stiffness—common causes include mechanical pressure, a drop in temperature, or chemical interactions with local anesthetic drugs such as lidocaine.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] Physical damage to the spinal cord may result in loss of sensation or movement.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] If an injury to the spine produces nothing worse than swelling, the symptoms may be transient, but if nerve fibers in the spine are actually destroyed, the loss of function is usually permanent.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] Experimental studies have shown that spinal nerve fibers attempt to regrow in the same way as nerve fibers, but in the spinal cord, tissue destruction usually produces scar tissue that cannot be penetrated by the regrowing nerves.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/nervous-system] Neurological practice draws heavily on the fields of neuroscience and psychiatry to treat diseases of the nervous system using various techniques of neurotherapy.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroglia] They also play a role in neurotransmission and synaptic connections, and in physiological processes such as breathing.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroglia] While glia were thought to outnumber neurons by a ratio of 10:1, studies using newer methods and reappraisal of historical quantitative evidence suggests an overall ratio of less than 1:1, with substantial variation between different brain tissues.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroglia] Glial cells have far more cellular diversity and functions than neurons, and can respond to and manipulate neurotransmission in multiple ways.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroglia] Additionally, they can affect both the preservation and consolidation of memories.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroglia] Glia were discovered in 1856, by the pathologist Rudolf Virchow in his search for a "connective tissue" in the brain.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroglia] The term derives from Greek γλία and γλοία "glue" (English: /ˈɡliːə/ or /ˈɡlaɪə/), and suggests the original impression that they were the glue of the nervous system.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroglia] Microglia are specialized macrophages capable of phagocytosis that protect neurons of the central nervous system.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroglia] They are derived from the earliest wave of mononuclear cells that originate in the blood islands of the yolk sac early in development, and colonize the brain shortly after the neural precursors begin to differentiate.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroglia] These cells are found in all regions of the brain and spinal cord.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroglia] Microglial cells are small relative to macroglial cells, with changing shapes and oblong nuclei.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroglia] They are mobile within the brain and multiply when the brain is damaged.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroglia] In the healthy central nervous system, microglia processes constantly sample all aspects of their environment (neurons, macroglia and blood vessels).
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroglia] In a healthy brain, microglia direct the immune response to brain damage and play an important role in the inflammation that accompanies the damage.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroglia] A number of diseases and disorders are associated with deficient microglia, such as Alzheimer's disease, Parkinson's disease and ALS.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroglia] Pituicytes from the posterior pituitary are glial cells with characteristics in common to astrocytes.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroglia] Tanycytes in the median eminence of the hypothalamus are a type of ependymal cell that descend from radial glia and line the base of the third ventricle.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroglia] *Drosophila melanogaster,* the fruit fly, contains a number of glial types that are functionally similar to mammalian glia but are nonetheless classified differently.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroglia] In general, neuroglial cells are smaller than neurons.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroglia] There are approximately 85 billion glial cells in the human brain, about the same number as neurons.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroglia] Glial cells make up about half the total volume of the brain and spinal cord.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroglia] The glia to neuron-ratio varies from one part of the brain to another.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroglia] The glia to neuron-ratio in the cerebral cortex is 3.72 (60.84 billion glia (72%); 16.34 billion neurons), while that of the cerebellum is only 0.23 (16.04 billion glia; 69.03 billion neurons).
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroglia] The ratio in the cerebral cortex gray matter is 1.48, with 3.76 for the gray and white matter combined.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroglia] The ratio of the basal ganglia, diencephalon and brainstem combined is 11.35.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroglia] The total number of glial cells in the human brain is distributed into the different types with oligodendrocytes being the most frequent (45–75%), followed by astrocytes (19–40%) and microglia (about 10% or less).
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroglia] Most glia are derived from ectodermal tissue of the developing embryo, in particular the neural tube and crest.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroglia] The exception is microglia, which are derived from hematopoietic stem cells.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroglia] In the adult, microglia are largely a self-renewing population and are distinct from macrophages and monocytes, which infiltrate an injured and diseased CNS.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroglia] In the central nervous system, glia develop from the ventricular zone of the neural tube.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroglia] These glia include the oligodendrocytes, ependymal cells, and astrocytes.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroglia] In the peripheral nervous system, glia derive from the neural crest.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroglia] These PNS glia include Schwann cells in nerves and satellite glial cells in ganglia.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroglia] Glia retain the ability to undergo cell divisions in adulthood, whereas most neurons cannot.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroglia] The view is based on the general inability of the mature nervous system to replace neurons after an injury, such as a stroke or trauma, where often there is a substantial proliferation of glia, or gliosis, near or at the site of damage.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroglia] However, detailed studies have found no evidence that 'mature' glia, such as astrocytes or oligodendrocytes, retain mitotic capacity.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroglia] Only the resident oligodendrocyte precursor cells seem to keep this ability once the nervous system matures.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroglia] Glial cells are known to be capable of mitosis.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroglia] By contrast, scientific understanding of whether neurons are permanently post-mitotic, or capable of mitosis, is still developing.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroglia] In the past, glia had been considered to lack certain features of neurons.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroglia] For example, glial cells were not believed to have chemical synapses or to release transmitters.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroglia] They were considered to be the passive bystanders of neural transmission.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroglia] However, recent studies have shown this to not be entirely true.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroglia] Some glial cells function primarily as the physical support for neurons.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroglia] Others provide nutrients to neurons and regulate the extracellular fluid of the brain, especially surrounding neurons and their synapses.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroglia] During early embryogenesis, glial cells direct the migration of neurons and produce molecules that modify the growth of axons and dendrites.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroglia] Some glial cells display regional diversity in the CNS and their functions may vary between the CNS regions.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroglia] Glia are crucial in the development of the nervous system and in processes such as synaptic plasticity and synaptogenesis.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroglia] Glia have a role in the regulation of repair of neurons after injury.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroglia] In the central nervous system (CNS), glia suppress repair.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroglia] Glial cells known as astrocytes enlarge and proliferate to form a scar and produce inhibitory molecules that inhibit regrowth of a damaged or severed axon.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroglia] In the peripheral nervous system (PNS), glial cells known as Schwann cells (or also as neuri-lemmocytes) promote repair.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroglia] After axonal injury, Schwann cells regress to an earlier developmental state to encourage regrowth of the axon.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroglia] This difference between the CNS and the PNS, raises hopes for the regeneration of nervous tissue in the CNS.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroglia] For example, a spinal cord may be able to be repaired following injury or severance.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroglia] Oligodendrocytes are found in the CNS and resemble an octopus: they have a bulbous cell body with up to fifteen arm-like processes.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroglia] Each process reaches out to an axon and spirals around it, creating a myelin sheath.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroglia] The myelin sheath insulates the nerve fiber from the extracellular fluid and speeds up signal conduction along the nerve fiber.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroglia] In the peripheral nervous system, Schwann cells are responsible for myelin production.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroglia] These cells envelop nerve fibers of the PNS by winding repeatedly around them.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroglia] This process creates a myelin sheath, which not only aids in conductivity but also assists in the regeneration of damaged fibers.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroglia] Astrocytes are crucial participants in the tripartite synapse.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroglia] They have several crucial functions, including clearance of neurotransmitters from within the synaptic cleft, which aids in distinguishing between separate action potentials and prevents toxic build-up of certain neurotransmitters such as glutamate, which would otherwise lead to excitotoxicity.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroglia] Furthermore, astrocytes release gliotransmitters such as glutamate, ATP, and D-serine in response to stimulation.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroglia] While glial cells in the PNS frequently assist in regeneration of lost neural functioning, loss of neurons in the CNS does not result in a similar reaction from neuroglia.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroglia] In the CNS, regrowth will only happen if the trauma was mild, and not severe.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroglia] When severe trauma presents itself, the survival of the remaining neurons becomes the optimal solution.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroglia] However, some studies investigating the role of glial cells in Alzheimer's disease are beginning to contradict the usefulness of this feature, and even claim it can "exacerbate" the disease.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroglia] In addition to affecting the potential repair of neurons in Alzheimer's disease, scarring and inflammation from glial cells have been further implicated in the degeneration of neurons caused by amyotrophic lateral sclerosis.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroglia] In addition to neurodegenerative diseases, a wide range of harmful exposure, such as hypoxia, or physical trauma, can lead to the result of physical damage to the CNS.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroglia] Generally, when damage occurs to the CNS, glial cells cause apoptosis among the surrounding cellular bodies.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroglia] Then, there is a large amount of microglial activity, which results in inflammation, and, finally, there is a heavy release of growth inhibiting molecules.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroglia] Glia were first described in 1856 by the pathologist Rudolf Virchow in a comment to his 1846 publication on connective tissue.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroglia] A more detailed description of glial cells was provided in the 1858 book 'Cellular Pathology' by the same author.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroglia] When markers for different types of cells were analyzed, Albert Einstein's brain was discovered to contain significantly more glia than normal brains in the left angular gyrus, an area thought to be responsible for mathematical processing and language.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroglia] However, out of the total of 28 statistical comparisons between Einstein's brain and the control brains, finding one statistically significant result is not surprising, and the claim that Einstein's brain is different is not scientific (cf. multiple comparisons problem).
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroglia] Not only does the ratio of glia to neurons increase through evolution, but so does the size of the glia.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroglia] Astroglial cells in human brains have a volume 27 times greater than in mouse brains.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroglia] These important scientific findings may begin to shift the neurocentric perspective into a more holistic view of the brain which encompasses the glial cells as well.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroglia] For the majority of the twentieth century, scientists had disregarded glial cells as mere physical scaffolds for neurons.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroglia] Recent publications have proposed that the number of glial cells in the brain is correlated with the intelligence of a species.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroglia] Moreover, evidences are demonstrating the active role of glia, in particular astroglia, in cognitive processes like learning and memory.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] The scope of neuroscience has broadened over time to include different approaches used to study the nervous system at different scales.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] The techniques used by neuroscientists have expanded enormously, from molecular and cellular studies of individual neurons to imaging of sensory, motor, and cognitive tasks in the brain.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] The earliest study of the nervous system dates to ancient Egypt.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] Trepanation, the surgical practice of either drilling or scraping a hole into the skull for the purpose of curing head injuries or mental disorders, or relieving cranial pressure, was first recorded during the Neolithic period.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] Manuscripts dating to 1700 BC indicate that the Egyptians had some knowledge about symptoms of brain damage.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] Early views on the function of the brain regarded it to be a "cranial stuffing" of sorts.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] In Egypt, from the late Middle Kingdom onwards, the brain was regularly removed in preparation for mummification.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] It was believed at the time that the heart was the seat of intelligence.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] Greek thinkers, beginning with Alcmaeon of Croton, advanced the cephalocentric hypothesis that the brain is the seat of sensation and thought.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] The view that the heart was the source of consciousness was not challenged until the time of the Greek physician Hippocrates.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] He believed that the brain was not only involved with sensation—since most specialized organs (e.g., eyes, ears, tongue) are located in the head near the brain—but was also the seat of intelligence.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] Plato also speculated that the brain was the seat of the rational part of the soul.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] Aristotle, however, believed the heart was the center of intelligence and that the brain regulated the amount of heat from the heart.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] This view was generally accepted until the Roman physician Galen, a follower of Hippocrates and physician to Roman gladiators, observed that his patients lost their mental faculties when they had sustained damage to their brains.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] Abulcasis, Averroes, Avicenna, Avenzoar, and Maimonides, active in the Medieval Muslim world, described a number of medical problems related to the brain.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] In Renaissance Europe, Vesalius (1514–1564), René Descartes (1596–1650), Thomas Willis (1621–1675) and Jan Swammerdam (1637–1680) also made several contributions to neuroscience.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] Luigi Galvani's pioneering work in the late 1700s set the stage for studying the electrical excitability of muscles and neurons.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] In 1843 Emil du Bois-Reymond demonstrated the electrical nature of the nerve signal, whose speed Hermann von Helmholtz proceeded to measure, and in 1875 Richard Caton found electrical phenomena in the cerebral hemispheres of rabbits and monkeys.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] Adolf Beck published in 1890 similar observations of spontaneous electrical activity of the brain of rabbits and dogs.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] Studies of the brain became more sophisticated after the invention of the microscope and the development of a staining procedure by Camillo Golgi during the late 1890s.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] The procedure used a silver chromate salt to reveal the intricate structures of individual neurons.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] His technique was used by Santiago Ramón y Cajal and led to the formation of the neuron doctrine, the hypothesis that the functional unit of the brain is the neuron.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] Golgi and Ramón y Cajal shared the Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine in 1906 for their extensive observations, descriptions, and categorizations of neurons throughout the brain.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] In parallel with this research, in 1815 Jean Pierre Flourens induced localized lesions of the brain in living animals to observe their effects on motricity, sensibility and behavior.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] Work with brain-damaged patients by Marc Dax in 1836 and Paul Broca in 1865 suggested that certain regions of the brain were responsible for certain functions.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] At the time, these findings were seen as a confirmation of Franz Joseph Gall's theory that language was localized and that certain psychological functions were localized in specific areas of the cerebral cortex.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] The localization of function hypothesis was supported by observations of epileptic patients conducted by John Hughlings Jackson, who correctly inferred the organization of the motor cortex by watching the progression of seizures through the body.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] Carl Wernicke further developed the theory of the specialization of specific brain structures in language comprehension and production.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] In 1894, neurologist and psychiatrist Edward Flatau published a human brain atlas “Atlas of the Human Brain and the Course of the Nerve-Fibres” which consisted of long-exposure photographs of fresh brain sections.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] In 1897, Charles Scott Sherrington introduced the name "synapse" for the connection between neurons.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] In 1909, German anatomist Korbinian Brodmann published his original research on brain mapping, defining 52 distinct regions of the cerebral cortex, known as Brodmann areas.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] Modern research through neuroimaging techniques, still uses the Brodmann cerebral cytoarchitectonic map (referring to the study of cell structure) anatomical definitions from this era in continuing to show that distinct areas of the cortex are activated in the execution of specific tasks.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] During the 20th century, neuroscience began to be recognized as a distinct academic discipline in its own right, rather than as studies of the nervous system within other disciplines.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] Eric Kandel and collaborators have cited David Rioch, Francis O.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] Schmitt, and Stephen Kuffler as having played critical roles in establishing the field.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] Rioch originated the integration of basic anatomical and physiological research with clinical psychiatry at the Walter Reed Army Institute of Research, starting in the 1950s.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] During the same period, Schmitt established a neuroscience research program within the Biology Department at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology, bringing together biology, chemistry, physics, and mathematics.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] The first freestanding neuroscience department (then called Psychobiology) was founded in 1964 at the University of California, Irvine by James L.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] This was followed by the Department of Neurobiology at Harvard Medical School, which was founded in 1966 by Stephen Kuffler.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] In the process of treating epilepsy, Wilder Penfield produced maps of the location of various functions (motor, sensory, memory, vision) in the brain.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] He summarized his findings in a 1950 book called *The Cerebral Cortex of Man*.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] Wilder Penfield and his co-investigators Edwin Boldrey and Theodore Rasmussen are considered to be the originators of the cortical homunculus.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] The understanding of neurons and of nervous system function became increasingly precise and molecular during the 20th century.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] For example, in 1952, Alan Lloyd Hodgkin and Andrew Huxley presented a mathematical model for the transmission of electrical signals in neurons of the giant axon of a squid, which they called "action potentials", and how they are initiated and propagated, known as the Hodgkin–Huxley model.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] Nagumo simplified Hodgkin–Huxley, in what is called the FitzHugh–Nagumo model.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] In 1962, Bernard Katz modeled neurotransmission across the space between neurons known as synapses.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] Beginning in 1966, Eric Kandel and collaborators examined biochemical changes in neurons associated with learning and memory storage in *Aplysia*.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] In 1981 Catherine Morris and Harold Lecar combined these models in the Morris–Lecar model.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] Such increasingly quantitative work gave rise to numerous biological neuron models and models of neural computation.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] As a result of the increasing interest about the nervous system, several prominent neuroscience organizations have been formed to provide a forum to all neuroscientists during the 20th century.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] For example, the International Brain Research Organization was founded in 1961, the International Society for Neurochemistry in 1963, the European Brain and Behaviour Society in 1968, and the Society for Neuroscience in 1969.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] Recently, the application of neuroscience research results has also given rise to applied disciplines as neuroeconomics, neuroeducation, neuroethics, and neurolaw.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] Over time, brain research has gone through philosophical, experimental, and theoretical phases, with work on neural implants and brain simulation predicted to be important in the future.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] The scientific study of the nervous system increased significantly during the second half of the twentieth century, principally due to advances in molecular biology, electrophysiology, and computational neuroscience.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] This has allowed neuroscientists to study the nervous system in all its aspects: how it is structured, how it works, how it develops, how it malfunctions, and how it can be changed.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] For example, it has become possible to understand, in much detail, the complex processes occurring within a single neuron.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] Neurons are cells specialized for communication.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] They are able to communicate with neurons and other cell types through specialized junctions called synapses, at which electrical or electrochemical signals can be transmitted from one cell to another.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] Many neurons extrude a long thin filament of axoplasm called an axon, which may extend to distant parts of the body and are capable of rapidly carrying electrical signals, influencing the activity of other neurons, muscles, or glands at their termination points.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] A nervous *system* emerges from the assemblage of neurons that are connected to each other in neural circuits, and networks.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] The vertebrate nervous system can be split into two parts: the central nervous system (defined as the brain and spinal cord), and the peripheral nervous system.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] In many species—including all vertebrates—the nervous system is the most complex organ system in the body, with most of the complexity residing in the brain.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] The human brain alone contains around one hundred billion neurons and one hundred trillion synapses; it consists of thousands of distinguishable substructures, connected to each other in synaptic networks whose intricacies have only begun to be unraveled.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] At least one out of three of the approximately 20,000 genes belonging to the human genome is expressed mainly in the brain.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] Due to the high degree of plasticity of the human brain, the structure of its synapses and their resulting functions change throughout life.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] Making sense of the nervous system's dynamic complexity is a formidable research challenge.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] Ultimately, neuroscientists would like to understand every aspect of the nervous system, including how it works, how it develops, how it malfunctions, and how it can be altered or repaired.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] Analysis of the nervous system is therefore performed at multiple levels, ranging from the molecular and cellular levels to the systems and cognitive levels.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] The specific topics that form the main focus of research change over time, driven by an ever-expanding base of knowledge and the availability of increasingly sophisticated technical methods.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] Improvements in technology have been the primary drivers of progress.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] Developments in electron microscopy, computer science, electronics, functional neuroimaging, and genetics and genomics have all been major drivers of progress.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] The efficiency of this method and the large amounts of data that is generated has allowed researchers to make some general conclusions about cell types; for example that the human and mouse brain have different versions of fundamentally the same cell types.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] Basic questions addressed in molecular neuroscience include the mechanisms by which neurons express and respond to molecular signals and how axons form complex connectivity patterns.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] At this level, tools from molecular biology and genetics are used to understand how neurons develop and how genetic changes affect biological functions.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] The morphology, molecular identity, and physiological characteristics of neurons and how they relate to different types of behavior are also of considerable interest.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] Questions addressed in cellular neuroscience include the mechanisms of how neurons process signals physiologically and electrochemically.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] These questions include how signals are processed by neurites and somas and how neurotransmitters and electrical signals are used to process information in a neuron.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] Neurites are thin extensions from a neuronal cell body, consisting of dendrites (specialized to receive synaptic inputs from other neurons) and axons (specialized to conduct nerve impulses called action potentials).
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] Somas are the cell bodies of the neurons and contain the nucleus.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] Another major area of cellular neuroscience is the investigation of the development of the nervous system.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] Questions include the patterning and regionalization of the nervous system, axonal and dendritic development, trophic interactions, synapse formation and the implication of fractones in neural stem cells, differentiation of neurons and glia (neurogenesis and gliogenesis), and neuronal migration.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] Computational neurogenetic modeling is concerned with the development of dynamic neuronal models for modeling brain functions with respect to genes and dynamic interactions between genes, on the cellular level (Computational Neurogenetic Modeling (CNGM) can also be used to model neural systems).
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] Systems neuroscience research centers on the structural and functional architecture of the developing human brain, and the functions of large-scale brain networks, or functionally-connected systems within the brain.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] Alongside brain development, systems neuroscience also focuses on how the structure and function of the brain enables or restricts the processing of sensory information, using learned mental models of the world, to motivate behavior.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] Questions in systems neuroscience include how neural circuits are formed and used anatomically and physiologically to produce functions such as reflexes, multisensory integration, motor coordination, circadian rhythms, emotional responses, learning, and memory.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] In other words, this area of research studies how connections are made and morphed in the brain, and the effect it has on human sensation, movement, attention, inhibitory control, decision-making, reasoning, memory formation, reward, and emotion regulation.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] Specific areas of interest for the field include observations of how the structure of neural circuits effect skill acquisition, how specialized regions of the brain develop and change (neuroplasticity), and the development of brain atlases, or wiring diagrams of individual developing brains.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] The related fields of neuroethology and neuropsychology address the question of how neural substrates underlie specific animal and human behaviors.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] Neuroendocrinology and psychoneuroimmunology examine interactions between the nervous system and the endocrine and immune systems, respectively.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] Despite many advancements, the way that networks of neurons perform complex cognitive processes and behaviors is still poorly understood.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] Cognitive neuroscience addresses the questions of how psychological functions are produced by neural circuitry.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] Although many studies hold a reductionist stance looking for the neurobiological basis of cognitive phenomena, recent research shows that there is an interplay between neuroscientific findings and conceptual research, soliciting and integrating both perspectives.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] For example, neuroscience research on empathy solicited an interdisciplinary debate involving philosophy, psychology and psychopathology.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] Moreover, the neuroscientific identification of multiple memory systems related to different brain areas has challenged the idea of memory as a literal reproduction of the past, supporting a view of memory as a generative, constructive and dynamic process.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] Neuroscience is also allied with the social and behavioral sciences, as well as with nascent interdisciplinary fields.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] Examples of such alliances include neuroeconomics, decision theory, social neuroscience, and neuromarketing to address complex questions about interactions of the brain with its environment.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] A study into consumer responses for example uses EEG to investigate neural correlates associated with narrative transportation into stories about energy efficiency.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] Questions in computational neuroscience can span a wide range of levels of traditional analysis, such as development, structure, and cognitive functions of the brain.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] Research in this field utilizes mathematical models, theoretical analysis, and computer simulation to describe and verify biologically plausible neurons and nervous systems.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] For example, biological neuron models are mathematical descriptions of spiking neurons which can be used to describe both the behavior of single neurons as well as the dynamics of neural networks.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] Computational neuroscience is often referred to as theoretical neuroscience.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] These terms also refer to clinical disciplines involving diagnosis and treatment of these diseases.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] Neurology works with diseases of the central and peripheral nervous systems, such as amyotrophic lateral sclerosis (ALS) and stroke, and their medical treatment.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] Psychiatry focuses on affective, behavioral, cognitive, and perceptual disorders.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] Anesthesiology focuses on perception of pain, and pharmacologic alteration of consciousness.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] Neuropathology focuses upon the classification and underlying pathogenic mechanisms of central and peripheral nervous system and muscle diseases, with an emphasis on morphologic, microscopic, and chemically observable alterations.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] Neurosurgery and psychosurgery work primarily with surgical treatment of diseases of the central and peripheral nervous systems.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] Neuroscience underlies the development of various neurotherapy methods to treat diseases of the nervous system.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] Recently, the boundaries between various specialties have blurred, as they are all influenced by basic research in neuroscience.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] For example, brain imaging enables objective biological insight into mental illnesses, which can lead to faster diagnosis, more accurate prognosis, and improved monitoring of patient progress over time.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] Integrative neuroscience describes the effort to combine models and information from multiple levels of research to develop a coherent model of the nervous system.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] For example, brain imaging coupled with physiological numerical models and theories of fundamental mechanisms may shed light on psychiatric disorders.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] Another important area of translational research is brain–computer interfaces (BCIs), or machines that are able to communicate and influence the brain.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] They are currently being researched for their potential to repair neural systems and restore certain cognitive functions.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] Translational BCI research is supported by specialized neurotechnology platforms that enable high-resolution neural signal acquisition, real-time processing, and experimental validation in clinical and laboratory settings.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] Such platforms are developed by academic groups as well as industry partners, including systems produced by g.tec medical engineering GmbH.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] Modern neuroscience education and research activities can be very roughly categorized into the following major branches, based on the subject and scale of the system in examination as well as distinct experimental or curricular approaches.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] Individual neuroscientists, however, often work on questions that span several distinct subfields.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] The career options for neuroscience graduates vary widely depending on the level of education.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] At the bachelor’s level, graduates often enter laboratory research, healthcare support, biotechnology, or science communication, though some pursue broader fields such as policy or nonprofit work.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] With a master’s degree, training may prepare individuals for applied health professions (e.g., occupational therapy, medicine -neurology, psychiatry, neuroimaging-, genetic counseling), research management, or public health.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] An advanced degree (PhD or equivalent) is usually required for independent research or university teaching.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] The largest professional neuroscience organization is the Society for Neuroscience (SFN), which is based in the United States but includes many members from other countries.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] Since its founding in 1969 the SFN has grown steadily: as of 2010 it recorded 40,290 members from 83 countries.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] Annual meetings, held each year in a different American city, draw attendance from researchers, postdoctoral fellows, graduate students, and undergraduates, as well as educational institutions, funding agencies, publishers, and hundreds of businesses that supply products used in research.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] FENS comprises a set of 32 national-level organizations, including the British Neuroscience Association, the German Neuroscience Society (*Neurowissenschaftliche Gesellschaft*), and the French **Société des Neurosciences**.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] The first National Honor Society in Neuroscience, Nu Rho Psi, was founded in 2006.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] Numerous youth neuroscience societies which support undergraduates, graduates and early career researchers also exist, such as Simply Neuroscience and Project Encephalon.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] In 2013, the BRAIN Initiative was announced in the US.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] The International Brain Initiative was created in 2017, currently integrated by more than seven national-level brain research initiatives (US, Europe, Allen Institute, Japan, China, Australia, Canada, Korea, and Israel) spanning four continents.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] In addition to conducting traditional research in laboratory settings, neuroscientists have also been involved in the promotion of awareness and knowledge about the nervous system among the general public and government officials.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] Such promotions have been done by both individual neuroscientists and large organizations.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] For example, individual neuroscientists have promoted neuroscience education among young students by organizing the International Brain Bee, which is an academic competition for high school or secondary school students worldwide.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] In Canada, the Canadian Institutes of Health Research's (CIHR) Canadian National Brain Bee is held annually at McMaster University.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] Neuroscience educators formed a Faculty for Undergraduate Neuroscience (FUN) in 1992 to share best practices and provide travel awards for undergraduates presenting at Society for Neuroscience meetings.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] Neuroscientists have also collaborated with other education experts to study and refine educational techniques to optimize learning among students, an emerging field called educational neuroscience.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] Federal agencies in the United States, such as the National Institute of Health (NIH) and National Science Foundation (NSF), have also funded research that pertains to best practices in teaching and learning of neuroscience concepts.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] Neuromorphic engineering is a branch of neuroscience that deals with creating functional physical models of neurons for the purposes of useful computation.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] The emergent computational properties of neuromorphic computers are fundamentally different from conventional computers in the sense that they are complex systems, and that the computational components are interrelated with no central processor.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] One example of such a computer is the SpiNNaker supercomputer.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] Sensors can also be made smart with neuromorphic technology.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] An example of this is the Event Camera's BrainScaleS (brain-inspired Multiscale Computation in Neuromorphic Hybrid Systems), a hybrid analog neuromorphic supercomputer located at Heidelberg University in Germany.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] It was developed as part of the Human Brain Project's neuromorphic computing platform and is the complement to the SpiNNaker supercomputer, which is based on digital technology.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/neuroscience] Recent advances in neuromorphic microchip technology have led a group of scientists to create an artificial neuron that can replace real neurons in diseases.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/peripheral-nervous-system] The **peripheral nervous system** (**PNS**) is one of two components that make up the nervous system of bilateral animals, with the other part being the central nervous system (CNS).
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/peripheral-nervous-system] The PNS consists of nerves and ganglia, which lie outside the brain and the spinal cord.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/peripheral-nervous-system] The main function of the PNS is to connect the CNS to the limbs and organs, essentially serving as a relay between the brain and spinal cord and the rest of the body.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/peripheral-nervous-system] Unlike the CNS, the PNS is not protected by the vertebral column and skull, which protect the CNS from physical injury or by the blood–brain barrier, which protects the CNS from blood-borne pathogens and toxins, leaving the PNS more vulnerable than the CNS.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/peripheral-nervous-system] The peripheral nervous system can be divided into a somatic division and an autonomic division.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/peripheral-nervous-system] Each of these can further be differentiated into a sensory and a motor sector.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/peripheral-nervous-system] In the somatic nervous system, the cranial nerves are part of the PNS with the exceptions of the olfactory nerve and epithelia and the optic nerve (cranial nerve II) along with the retina, which are considered parts of the central nervous system based on developmental origin.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/peripheral-nervous-system] The second cranial nerve is not a true peripheral nerve but a tract of the diencephalon.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/peripheral-nervous-system] Cranial nerve ganglia, as with all ganglia, are part of the PNS.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/peripheral-nervous-system] The autonomic nervous system exerts involuntary control over smooth muscle and glands.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/peripheral-nervous-system] The peripheral nervous system can be divided into a somatic and an autonomic division, which are part of the somatic nervous system and the autonomic nervous system, respectively.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/peripheral-nervous-system] The somatic nervous system is under voluntary control, and transmits signals from the brain to end organs such as muscles.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/peripheral-nervous-system] The sensory nervous system is part of the somatic nervous system and transmits signals from senses such as taste and touch (including fine touch and gross touch) to the spinal cord and brain.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/peripheral-nervous-system] The autonomic nervous system is a "self-regulating" system which influences the function of organs outside voluntary control, such as the heart rate, or the functions of the digestive system.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/peripheral-nervous-system] The somatic nervous system includes the sensory nervous system (ex. the somatosensory system) and consists of sensory nerves and somatic nerves, and many nerves which hold both functions.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/peripheral-nervous-system] In the head and neck, cranial nerves carry somatosensory data.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/peripheral-nervous-system] There are twelve cranial nerves, ten of which originate from the brainstem, and mainly control the functions of the anatomic structures of the head with some exceptions.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/peripheral-nervous-system] One unique cranial nerve is the vagus nerve, which receives sensory information from organs in the thorax and abdomen.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/peripheral-nervous-system] The other unique cranial nerve is the accessory nerve which is responsible for innervating the sternocleidomastoid and trapezius muscles, neither of which are located exclusively in the head.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/peripheral-nervous-system] For the rest of the body, spinal nerves are responsible for somatosensory information.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/peripheral-nervous-system] Usually these arise as a web ("plexus") of interconnected nerves roots that arrange to form single nerves.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/peripheral-nervous-system] These nerves control the functions of the rest of the body.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/peripheral-nervous-system] In humans, there are 31 pairs of spinal nerves: 8 cervical, 12 thoracic, 5 lumbar, 5 sacral, and 1 coccygeal.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/peripheral-nervous-system] These nerve roots are named according to the spinal vertebrata which they are adjacent to.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/peripheral-nervous-system] In the cervical region, the spinal nerve roots come out *above* the corresponding vertebrae (i.e., nerve root between the skull and 1st cervical vertebrae is called spinal nerve C1).
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/peripheral-nervous-system] From the thoracic region to the coccygeal region, the spinal nerve roots come out *below* the corresponding vertebrae.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/peripheral-nervous-system] This method creates a problem when naming the spinal nerve root between C7 and T1 (so it is called spinal nerve root C8).
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/peripheral-nervous-system] In the lumbar and sacral region, the spinal nerve roots travel within the dural sac and they travel below the level of L2 as the cauda equina.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/peripheral-nervous-system] The first 4 cervical spinal nerves, C1 through C4, split and recombine to produce a variety of nerves that serve the neck and back of head.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/peripheral-nervous-system] Spinal nerve C1 is called the suboccipital nerve, which provides motor innervation to muscles at the base of the skull.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/peripheral-nervous-system] C2 and C3 form many of the nerves of the neck, providing both sensory and motor control.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/peripheral-nervous-system] These include the greater occipital nerve, which provides sensation to the back of the head, the lesser occipital nerve, which provides sensation to the area behind the ears, the greater auricular nerve and the lesser auricular nerve.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/peripheral-nervous-system] The phrenic nerve is a nerve essential for our survival which arises from nerve roots C3, C4 and C5.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/peripheral-nervous-system] It supplies the thoracic diaphragm, enabling breathing.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/peripheral-nervous-system] If the spinal cord is transected above C3, then spontaneous breathing is not possible.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/peripheral-nervous-system] The last four cervical spinal nerves, C5 through C8, and the first thoracic spinal nerve, T1, combine to form the brachial plexus, or plexus brachialis, a tangled array of nerves, splitting, combining and recombining, to form the nerves that subserve the upper-limb and upper back.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/peripheral-nervous-system] Although the brachial plexus may appear tangled, it is highly organized and predictable, with little variation between people.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/peripheral-nervous-system] The anterior divisions of the lumbar nerves, sacral nerves, and coccygeal nerve form the lumbosacral plexus, the first lumbar nerve being frequently joined by a branch from the twelfth thoracic.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/peripheral-nervous-system] The autonomic nervous system (ANS) controls involuntary responses to regulate physiological functions.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/peripheral-nervous-system] The brain and spinal cord of the central nervous system are connected with organs that have smooth muscle or cardiac muscle, such as the heart, bladder, and other cardiac, exocrine, and endocrine related organs, by ganglionic neurons.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/peripheral-nervous-system] The most notable physiological effects from autonomic activity are pupil constriction and dilation, and salivation of saliva.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/peripheral-nervous-system] The autonomic nervous system is always activated, but is either in the sympathetic or parasympathetic state.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/peripheral-nervous-system] Depending on the situation, one state can overshadow the other, resulting in a release of different kinds of neurotransmitters.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/peripheral-nervous-system] The sympathetic system is activated during a "fight or flight" situation in which mental stress or physical danger is encountered.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/peripheral-nervous-system] Neurotransmitters such as norepinephrine, and epinephrine are released, which increases heart rate and blood flow in certain areas like muscle, while simultaneously decreasing activities of non-critical functions for survival, like digestion.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/peripheral-nervous-system] The systems are independent to each other, which allows activation of certain parts of the body, while others remain rested.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/peripheral-nervous-system] Primarily using the neurotransmitter acetylcholine (ACh) as a mediator, the parasympathetic system allows the body to function in a "rest and digest" state.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/peripheral-nervous-system] Consequently, when the parasympathetic system dominates the body, there are increases in salivation and activities in digestion, while heart rate and other sympathetic response decrease.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/peripheral-nervous-system] Unlike the sympathetic system, humans have some voluntary controls in the parasympathetic system.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/peripheral-nervous-system] The most prominent examples of this control are urination and defecation.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/peripheral-nervous-system] There is a lesser known division of the autonomic nervous system known as the enteric nervous system.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/peripheral-nervous-system] Located only around the digestive tract, this system allows for local control without input from the sympathetic or the parasympathetic branches, though it can still receive and respond to signals from the rest of the body.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/peripheral-nervous-system] The enteric system is responsible for various functions related to gastrointestinal system.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/peripheral-nervous-system] Diseases of the peripheral nervous system can be specific to one or more nerves, or affect the system as a whole.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/peripheral-nervous-system] Any peripheral nerve or nerve root can be damaged, called a mononeuropathy.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/peripheral-nervous-system] Such injuries can be because of injury or trauma, or compression.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/peripheral-nervous-system] Compression of nerves can occur because of a tumour mass or injury.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/peripheral-nervous-system] Alternatively, if a nerve is in an area with a fixed size it may be trapped if the other components increase in size, such as carpal tunnel syndrome and tarsal tunnel syndrome.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/peripheral-nervous-system] Common symptoms of carpal tunnel syndrome include pain and numbness in the thumb, index and middle finger.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/peripheral-nervous-system] In peripheral neuropathy, the function one or more nerves are damaged through a variety of means.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/peripheral-nervous-system] Toxic damage may occur because of diabetes (diabetic neuropathy), alcohol, heavy metals or other toxins; some infections; autoimmune and inflammatory conditions such as amyloidosis and sarcoidosis.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/peripheral-nervous-system] Peripheral neuropathy is associated with a sensory loss in a "glove and stocking" distribution that begins at the peripheral and slowly progresses upwards, and may also be associated with acute and chronic pain.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/peripheral-nervous-system] Peripheral neuropathy is not just limited to the somatosensory nerves, but the autonomic nervous system too (autonomic neuropathy).
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/reflex-arc] A **reflex arc** is a neural pathway that controls a reflex.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/reflex-arc] In vertebrates, most sensory neurons synapse in the spinal cord and the signal then travels through it into the brain.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/reflex-arc] This allows for faster reflex actions to occur by activating spinal motor neurons without the delay of routing signals through the brain.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/reflex-arc] The brain will receive the input while the reflex is being carried out and the analysis of the signal takes place after the reflex action.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/reflex-arc] There are two types: autonomic reflex arc (affecting inner organs) and somatic reflex arc (affecting muscles).
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/reflex-arc] Autonomic reflexes sometimes involve the spinal cord and some somatic reflexes are mediated more by the brain than the spinal cord.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/reflex-arc] *Effector* muscle innervated by the efferent nerve fiber carries out the response.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/reflex-arc] A reflex arc, then, is the pathway followed by nerves which (a.) carry sensory information from the receptor to the spinal cord, and then (b.) carry the response generated by the spinal cord to effector organs during a reflex action.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/reflex-arc] The pathway taken by the nerve impulse to accomplish a reflex action is called the reflex arc.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/reflex-arc] When a reflex arc in an animal consists of only one sensory neuron and one motor neuron, it is defined as **monosynaptic**, referring to the presence of a single chemical synapse.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/reflex-arc] In the case of peripheral muscle reflexes (patellar reflex, achilles reflex), brief stimulation to the muscle spindle results in contraction of the agonist or effector muscle.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/reflex-arc] By contrast, in **polysynaptic** reflex pathways, one or more interneurons connect afferent (sensory) and efferent (motor) signals.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/reflex-arc] All but the most simple reflexes are polysynaptic, allowing processing or inhibition of polysynaptic reflexes within the brain.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/reflex-arc] When the patellar tendon is tapped just below the knee, the tap initiates an action potential in a specialized structure known as a muscle spindle located within the quadriceps.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/reflex-arc] This action potential travels to the L3 and L4 nerve roots of the spinal cord, via a sensory axon which chemically communicates by releasing glutamate onto a motor nerve.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/reflex-arc] The result of this motor nerve activity is contraction of the quadriceps muscle, leading to extension of the lower leg at the knee (i.e. the lower leg kicks forward).
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/reflex-arc] Ultimately, an improper patellar reflex may indicate an injury of the central nervous system.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/reflex-arc] The sensory input from the quadriceps also activates local interneurons that release the inhibitory neurotransmitter glycine onto motor neurons of antagonist muscles, blocking their stimulation (in this case the hamstring muscles).
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/reflex-arc] The relaxation of the opposing muscle facilitates (by not opposing) the extension of the lower leg.
[src:neuroscience-fundamentals/reflex-arc] In invertebrates reflex interneurons do not necessarily reside in the spinal cord, for example as in the lateral giant neuron of crayfish.
